00:00:23.250 --> 00:00:24.000
MICHAEL SHORT: OK.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.375
I think things have been
getting pretty derivy lately,

00:00:26.375 --> 00:00:28.750
so I wanted to shift gears to
something a little bit more

00:00:28.750 --> 00:00:30.070
practical.

00:00:30.070 --> 00:00:33.310
So I started alluding to this
hypothetical radiation source

00:00:33.310 --> 00:00:35.697
I might have right
here, and things

00:00:35.697 --> 00:00:37.780
like if you have a source
of known activity, which

00:00:37.780 --> 00:00:40.000
we calculated
yesterday, and you have

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.210
a detector of
unknown efficiency,

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:45.940
how do you know what
the efficiency is?

00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:48.220
How do you know what, let's say,
your dose distance relationship

00:00:48.220 --> 00:00:48.903
is?

00:00:48.903 --> 00:00:50.570
And how do you calculate
all this stuff?

00:00:50.570 --> 00:00:54.130
So let's take the general
situation that we're

00:00:54.130 --> 00:00:56.090
starting to work out.

00:00:56.090 --> 00:00:59.210
Let's say we have a
Geiger counter right here.

00:00:59.210 --> 00:01:01.150
That's our GM tube.

00:01:01.150 --> 00:01:07.870
And we have a
point source that's

00:01:07.870 --> 00:01:10.905
emitting things
in all directions.

00:01:10.905 --> 00:01:12.530
Let's go with the
stuff from yesterday.

00:01:12.530 --> 00:01:14.000
Let's say it's a
cobalt 60 source.

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:23.210
It's now 0.52 microcurie.

00:01:23.210 --> 00:01:26.810
The question is, how many counts
do you expect in this detector

00:01:26.810 --> 00:01:29.030
when it's a certain
distance away?

00:01:29.030 --> 00:01:31.460
So I've actually laser-cut out
a little Geiger counter jig

00:01:31.460 --> 00:01:32.480
from a previous class.

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:34.370
And you guys can
all do this too.

00:01:34.370 --> 00:01:36.890
Who here has been
to the IDC before?

00:01:36.890 --> 00:01:37.430
A couple.

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:38.805
The international
design center--

00:01:38.805 --> 00:01:41.430
so they've got a laser cutter
that you can sign up to use,

00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:43.020
which is where I did this.

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:45.770
And it's set to just
take a Geiger counter

00:01:45.770 --> 00:01:48.620
and put your sources
at some fixed distance

00:01:48.620 --> 00:01:51.410
away so you can discover
the dose distance

00:01:51.410 --> 00:01:53.060
relationship with things.

00:01:53.060 --> 00:01:55.250
Speaking of, does anybody
know what the relationship

00:01:55.250 --> 00:01:58.545
is between dose and distance or
measured activity and distance?

00:02:01.970 --> 00:02:02.830
Yeah, Luke.

00:02:02.830 --> 00:02:04.080
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] r cubed.

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:05.310
MICHAEL SHORT: Close.

00:02:05.310 --> 00:02:08.190
It's, let's say, the
measured activity

00:02:08.190 --> 00:02:15.000
would be proportional
to 1 over r squared.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.170
Who knows where this comes from?

00:02:18.170 --> 00:02:20.500
I'll move the source a bit
away to lessen the beeping.

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:23.820
Yeah.

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:25.860
AUDIENCE: Well, the flux
of particles coming out

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:31.508
is just [INAUDIBLE] over the
surface area of [INAUDIBLE]

00:02:31.508 --> 00:02:34.890
and the [INAUDIBLE]
is 4 pi r squared.

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:36.240
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah, exactly.

00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:39.720
If you were to draw
a hypothetical sphere

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:43.170
around the source right
here, then you've got,

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:45.750
let's say, a detector
that's roughly rectangular

00:02:45.750 --> 00:02:47.220
with a fixed area.

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:50.850
Let's say it's got a half
length L and a half width

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:53.340
W. Then the area--

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:56.730
I'm sorry, let's just
say length L, width W--

00:02:56.730 --> 00:03:00.900
would be just L times
W. And actually,

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:05.130
what Chris mentioned as
the solid angle subtended

00:03:05.130 --> 00:03:07.230
by this detector right here--

00:03:07.230 --> 00:03:11.340
in other words, at a
certain distance r away,

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:13.273
how much of this sphere--

00:03:13.273 --> 00:03:15.690
how much does the area of this
sphere-- does this detector

00:03:15.690 --> 00:03:16.797
take up?

00:03:16.797 --> 00:03:18.630
In other words, how
many of these gamma rays

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:21.360
are going to go in a different
direction than the detector,

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:24.450
versus how many we'll
actually enter the detector?

00:03:24.450 --> 00:03:26.640
And a simple formula
for the solid angle

00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:29.400
is just the surface
area of whatever

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:34.490
you've got over r squared.

00:03:34.490 --> 00:03:37.610
It's a pretty good approximation
to the solid angle of something

00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:40.278
for very long distances,
and it's probably the one

00:03:40.278 --> 00:03:41.570
that you'll see in the reading.

00:03:41.570 --> 00:03:45.290
But I wanted to show you the
actual formula, in this case,

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:46.970
for a rectangle--

00:03:46.970 --> 00:03:48.750
solid angle comparison.

00:03:48.750 --> 00:03:49.970
Good, that's up there.

00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:56.400
So let's say on the
x-axis, right here,

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:59.940
this would be distance
from the source

00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:01.405
to the detector in meters.

00:04:01.405 --> 00:04:03.780
And I've said that we've got
some sort of a detector that

00:04:03.780 --> 00:04:06.540
is 2.5 by 10 meters in size.

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:08.550
That's an enormous detector.

00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:10.620
Let's actually switch it
to the units right here.

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:15.480
So this is roughly
10 centimeters long.

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:19.910
So let's change
our length to 0.1.

00:04:19.910 --> 00:04:23.150
And what do you think the
width of this Geiger counter

00:04:23.150 --> 00:04:24.792
is in meters?

00:04:24.792 --> 00:04:26.085
AUDIENCE: A centimeter

00:04:26.085 --> 00:04:28.410
MICHAEL SHORT: A centimeter.

00:04:28.410 --> 00:04:31.325
0.01.

00:04:31.325 --> 00:04:33.700
We're going to have to change
our axes so we can actually

00:04:33.700 --> 00:04:34.330
see the graph.

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:37.620
So instead of looking all the
way out to 15 meters away,

00:04:37.620 --> 00:04:39.870
let's look one meter
away, maybe less.

00:04:39.870 --> 00:04:42.736
This whole thing is
probably 50 centimeters.

00:04:46.210 --> 00:04:48.140
And we'll take a look there.

00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:51.260
And what we notice is
that except for extremely

00:04:51.260 --> 00:04:54.980
short distances, this
approximate formula

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:57.420
for the solid angle--
or in other words,

00:04:57.420 --> 00:05:01.820
if I were to draw a sphere
around the source that's

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:03.823
the radius of the distance
between the source

00:05:03.823 --> 00:05:05.240
and the detector,
how much of that

00:05:05.240 --> 00:05:08.060
sphere's area does
the detector take up?

00:05:08.060 --> 00:05:11.330
This approximate
formula-- the blue curve--

00:05:11.330 --> 00:05:13.760
is a pretty good
approximation of the red curve

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:16.970
until you get really, really
close to 5 centimeters

00:05:16.970 --> 00:05:20.180
away, or about this
distance right here.

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:24.860
Does anyone know why this
formula would break down?

00:05:24.860 --> 00:05:28.980
What happens as r goes to 0?

00:05:31.510 --> 00:05:34.330
What happens to our solid
angle or our approximation

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:36.800
for our solid angle?

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:38.106
AUDIENCE: Goes to Infinity

00:05:38.106 --> 00:05:41.000
MICHAEL SHORT: It goes
to infinity, right?

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.820
Can a detector actually
take up infinity area

00:05:43.820 --> 00:05:45.950
on, well, anything?

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:47.900
Never mind that unit sphere.

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:49.140
Not quite.

00:05:49.140 --> 00:05:52.250
If you were to take this
detector and bring the radius

00:05:52.250 --> 00:05:55.730
down to 0 so that the
source and the detector,

00:05:55.730 --> 00:05:58.130
if not counting for the
thickness of the plastic,

00:05:58.130 --> 00:06:02.295
were right upside each other, if
that solid angle went to, well,

00:06:02.295 --> 00:06:04.295
infinity , then the count
should go to infinity,

00:06:04.295 --> 00:06:07.590
and it does not compute.

00:06:07.590 --> 00:06:09.770
Does anyone know how many--

00:06:09.770 --> 00:06:13.760
first of all, who here has
heard of solid angle before?

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:16.878
So a little more
than half of you.

00:06:16.878 --> 00:06:17.795
That's getting clicky.

00:06:17.795 --> 00:06:19.880
I'm going to turn that off.

00:06:19.880 --> 00:06:22.320
Solid angle is kind of the
analog to regular old angle,

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:24.090
except in 3D.

00:06:24.090 --> 00:06:26.880
So instead of looking
at things in radians,

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:31.630
this has the unit of
what's called steradians--

00:06:31.630 --> 00:06:44.220
steradians-- with a full sphere
taking up 4pi steradians.

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:46.290
Interestingly
enough, 4pi is also

00:06:46.290 --> 00:06:49.757
the surface area of a unit
sphere with radius of 1.

00:06:49.757 --> 00:06:51.090
So that's where this comes from.

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:54.660
If something were to completely
cover a unit sphere--

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:58.042
like, if you were to, let's say,
encase a light source in tin

00:06:58.042 --> 00:07:01.470
foil completely, and say,
how much of that solid angle

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:02.640
does the tin foil encase?

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:05.580
It would be 4pi
steradians, regardless

00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:10.310
of the size of the sphere or how
much tin foil you had to use.

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:13.840
So this pretty simple formula
isn't the best approximation

00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:14.340
for it.

00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:16.432
And I'm not going to go
through the derivation,

00:07:16.432 --> 00:07:17.890
because like I
said, today is going

00:07:17.890 --> 00:07:20.120
to be a more practical nature.

00:07:20.120 --> 00:07:22.730
There is a more complex
and rigorous formula

00:07:22.730 --> 00:07:25.670
for the solid
angle of something,

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:28.550
let's say, in this case,
a rectangle of length L

00:07:28.550 --> 00:07:33.080
and with W, from a certain
distance r, or, in this case,

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:35.530
on our graph, x away
from the sphere.

00:07:35.530 --> 00:07:38.115
And you can actually see
that red curve right there.

00:07:38.115 --> 00:07:39.740
Once you get to a
few centimeters away,

00:07:39.740 --> 00:07:42.650
it's pretty close.

00:07:42.650 --> 00:07:46.340
Anyone want to guess what the
maximum value of the red curve

00:07:46.340 --> 00:07:48.600
is?

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:50.940
If I take this source
and slam it right up next

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:57.000
to the detector,
how much of sphere

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.902
is the detector subtending?

00:07:59.902 --> 00:08:00.800
AUDIENCE: 2pi

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:02.960
MICHAEL SHORT: 2pi--
half the sphere.

00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:05.240
Because let's say this
whole side of the source

00:08:05.240 --> 00:08:08.390
is completely obscured by the
detector and this whole side

00:08:08.390 --> 00:08:10.310
is free to move.

00:08:10.310 --> 00:08:13.990
And if you look really closely,
yep, at 0, the correct formula

00:08:13.990 --> 00:08:16.130
does give you 2pi steradians.

00:08:16.130 --> 00:08:18.970
Which is to say that half the
gamma rays leaving the source

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:21.010
would enter the detector.

00:08:21.010 --> 00:08:23.860
I didn't say anything
about get counted yet.

00:08:23.860 --> 00:08:26.130
That's where the detector
efficiency comes in.

00:08:26.130 --> 00:08:28.570
And that's something we're
going to be measuring today,

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:32.140
which is why I have my
big bag of burnt bananas.

00:08:32.140 --> 00:08:35.710
These are the ashes of roughly
50 pounds of bananas charred

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:39.490
to a crisp at about 250
Fahrenheit for 12 hours in most

00:08:39.490 --> 00:08:42.549
of the dorms and a couple
of the frat houses.

00:08:42.549 --> 00:08:45.040
So last year, I had the
students, everyone, take home

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:47.018
about 50 pounds of
bananas or 50 bananas--

00:08:47.018 --> 00:08:47.810
I forget which one.

00:08:47.810 --> 00:08:49.450
It was a lot.

00:08:49.450 --> 00:08:50.890
And we did some
distributed labor.

00:08:50.890 --> 00:08:53.890
So everybody peeled the
bananas, put them in the oven,

00:08:53.890 --> 00:08:56.530
baked them, separated
off the tin foil,

00:08:56.530 --> 00:08:58.480
baked off as much water
and sugar as possible

00:08:58.480 --> 00:09:01.882
to concentrate the
potassium 40 in the banana.

00:09:01.882 --> 00:09:03.340
So there's a reason
I've been using

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:06.700
potassium 40 as a lot of
examples in this class,

00:09:06.700 --> 00:09:08.560
because you're full of it.

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:10.690
That's pretty much the
short answer of it.

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:11.740
If you eat bananas--

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:13.510
which, I think most
of you guys do--

00:09:13.510 --> 00:09:16.060
you're intaking a fair bit of
radioactive potassium, which

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:18.880
is a positron
emitter, and also it

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:21.800
does electron capture
and all that fun stuff.

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:23.650
So today, what we're
going to be doing

00:09:23.650 --> 00:09:28.050
is calculating the
activity of one banana.

00:09:28.050 --> 00:09:30.360
But that's kind of a very
difficult thing to do.

00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:33.150
So anyone know how radioactive
one banana actually

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:35.490
is in any units at all?

00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:42.250
Whatever it is, it's very,
very, very, very little.

00:09:42.250 --> 00:09:45.070
One banana contains a
minuscule but measurable amount

00:09:45.070 --> 00:09:46.630
of radioactivity.

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:48.970
And one of the ways to
boost your confidence

00:09:48.970 --> 00:09:50.470
on any sort of
radiation measurement

00:09:50.470 --> 00:09:54.360
is to boost your signal strength
or to boost your counting time.

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:57.190
And because I don't want to
count for the next seven years,

00:09:57.190 --> 00:10:00.700
we've concentrated the ashes
of 50 pounds of bananas in here

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:02.980
to boost your signal
strength, which

00:10:02.980 --> 00:10:05.290
is going to boost
your count rate, which

00:10:05.290 --> 00:10:08.830
is the intro I want to give
to statistics certainty

00:10:08.830 --> 00:10:11.560
and counting.

00:10:11.560 --> 00:10:15.070
So let's take one of
the homework problems

00:10:15.070 --> 00:10:17.163
as a motivating example.

00:10:17.163 --> 00:10:19.330
You guys, did anyone notice
the extra credit problem

00:10:19.330 --> 00:10:21.170
on the homework?

00:10:21.170 --> 00:10:24.462
Let's start talking about
how we'd go about that.

00:10:24.462 --> 00:10:26.170
That should motivate
the rest of the day.

00:10:29.930 --> 00:10:33.660
So I'll pull up that
problem set, number 4--

00:10:33.660 --> 00:10:35.730
which, by the way, is due
Thursday, not Tuesday,

00:10:35.730 --> 00:10:38.950
because we have no
class on Tuesday.

00:10:38.950 --> 00:10:41.170
That was a surprise
to me, but whatever.

00:10:44.230 --> 00:10:45.700
I'll still be here.

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:46.995
We don't get holidays--

00:10:46.995 --> 00:10:47.650
just you guys.

00:10:51.420 --> 00:10:54.770
So bonus question-- go do this.

00:10:54.770 --> 00:10:58.412
So we all know that smoking is
a major source of radioactivity.

00:10:58.412 --> 00:10:59.870
And if you think
about it, it's not

00:10:59.870 --> 00:11:02.540
just the smoke that contains
those radiation particles,

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:04.160
it's got to be the
cigarettes, cigars,

00:11:04.160 --> 00:11:06.180
and other smokables themselves.

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:09.140
And so I was thinking, there's
no better concentrated source

00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:11.095
of smoking radioactivity
than a smoke shop.

00:11:11.095 --> 00:11:13.220
There's one out at [INAUDIBLE]
at the end of the T.

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:15.440
There's probably some
closer to campus.

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:17.840
But I know there's a whole
bunch that are T accessible.

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:20.150
And so I was thinking it'd
be neat for us to find out,

00:11:20.150 --> 00:11:23.710
how radioactive is it
to work in a smoke shop?

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:26.030
Because there's all these
radon decay-- oh, yeah?

00:11:26.030 --> 00:11:26.780
You actually know.

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:29.030
AUDIENCE: You know you have to
be 21 to go into a smoke shop?

