At any rate, I would
think that, OK,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.790
it's probably a fairly
radioactive place to work.

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:13.100
But the question is, how
long would you actually have

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:15.560
to bring a detector
in and count in order

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:19.130
to be sure that there's any
sort of measurable difference?

00:12:19.130 --> 00:12:22.880
And so, without deriving all
of this stuff about binomial,

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:25.100
Poisson, and normal
statistics, I'll say,

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:26.810
that's in the reading for today.

00:12:26.810 --> 00:12:28.790
I want to show you
some practical uses

00:12:28.790 --> 00:12:30.800
and applications of this stuff.

00:12:30.800 --> 00:12:33.410
Let's say you were
to measure some count

00:12:33.410 --> 00:12:35.580
rate in some experiment.

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:39.660
And we'll put this in
units of counts per minute,

00:12:39.660 --> 00:12:43.040
which would be the number of
counts divided by the counting

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:43.670
time.

00:12:43.670 --> 00:12:46.750
That's about as
simple as it gets.

00:12:46.750 --> 00:12:49.950
From Poisson
statistics, you can say

00:12:49.950 --> 00:12:54.940
that the standard deviation
of that count rate

00:12:54.940 --> 00:13:00.280
is actually just the square
root of the count rate divided

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:01.430
by time.

00:13:01.430 --> 00:13:04.390
And that's kind of the
simple thing right here.

00:13:04.390 --> 00:13:06.430
But usually, in these
sorts of experiments,

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:08.740
if you want to know how
much more radioactive is

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:12.530
one place than another, you
have to take a background count.

00:13:12.530 --> 00:13:15.490
So if I wanted to know how much
activity that source was giving

00:13:15.490 --> 00:13:18.100
off, there is lots of
background radiation

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:20.290
that we'll be going
over in about a month.

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:23.320
I would have to sit
here for quite a while

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:26.110
and wait for the slow clicks
of whatever background

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:28.370
radiation is in the room--

00:13:28.370 --> 00:13:32.365
there we go-- to get enough
of a count right going on.

00:13:32.365 --> 00:13:35.368
As you can imagine, the
slower the count rate,

00:13:35.368 --> 00:13:37.660
the less certain you can be
that the number that you're

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:39.770
measuring is actually accurate.

00:13:39.770 --> 00:13:42.370
So the idea here is that
this standard deviation

00:13:42.370 --> 00:13:46.270
is a measure of confidence that
your value is actually right.

00:13:46.270 --> 00:13:50.920
So the two things that
you could do to decrease

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:52.810
this standard deviation--

00:13:52.810 --> 00:13:57.440
you could increase
your counting time.

00:13:57.440 --> 00:13:58.510
Why is there a C on top?

00:13:58.510 --> 00:14:00.020
That doesn't look right.

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:01.260
It actually is OK.

00:14:01.260 --> 00:14:02.480
Yeah.

00:14:02.480 --> 00:14:04.190
Yeah, there we go.

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:06.310
So by counting for
longer you can decrease

00:14:06.310 --> 00:14:08.620
your standard deviation.

00:14:08.620 --> 00:14:10.330
This is going to take forever.

00:14:10.330 --> 00:14:12.400
It actually takes
about 67 minutes,

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:14.290
because we've already
done this calculation,

00:14:14.290 --> 00:14:18.273
to get a 95% confidence
on 5% uncertainty

00:14:18.273 --> 00:14:19.690
for this sort of
background count.

00:14:19.690 --> 00:14:22.540
I mean, how many counts
we have so far, like, 12?

00:14:22.540 --> 00:14:24.000
14?

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.590
Yeah, not very many.

00:14:26.590 --> 00:14:29.230
Then you've got to be able
to subtract that count

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:33.010
rate from whatever your
source actually is.

00:14:33.010 --> 00:14:35.080
And the way that you
actually measure this

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:37.000
is pretty straightforward.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:38.830
The way that you do
error subtraction

00:14:38.830 --> 00:14:41.653
is not as straightforward.

00:14:41.653 --> 00:14:43.570
So let's say we're going
to separate these two

00:14:43.570 --> 00:14:48.870
experiments into a
background experiment, which

00:14:48.870 --> 00:14:50.610
we're actually going
to do in an hour.

00:14:50.610 --> 00:14:52.318
When we want to count
these banana ashes,

00:14:52.318 --> 00:14:54.600
we're going to have
to count radiation

00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:57.060
coming from the detector
itself, which will account

00:14:57.060 --> 00:15:00.780
for cosmic rays, contamination
in the detector, whatever else

00:15:00.780 --> 00:15:03.120
might have been spilled in
there from previous samples.

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:08.860
And we're also going to take
some sort of gross count

00:15:08.860 --> 00:15:15.440
rate, which will be our
background plus the net count

00:15:15.440 --> 00:15:17.060
rate of our actual source.

00:15:17.060 --> 00:15:19.360
And that's what we're going for.

00:15:19.360 --> 00:15:22.245
So the net count
rate is pretty easy.

00:15:22.245 --> 00:15:25.070
It's just the gross count
rate minus the background--

00:15:25.070 --> 00:15:27.720
let's keep the
symbols the same--

00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:28.860
count rate.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:34.220
Does anyone know how to
quantify the uncertainty

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:37.510
of this net count rate?

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:38.670
Do you just add the two?

00:15:48.285 --> 00:15:50.410
Well, in this case, we have
to account for the fact

00:15:50.410 --> 00:15:53.800
that radiation
emission from anything

00:15:53.800 --> 00:15:56.020
is a truly random process.

00:15:56.020 --> 00:15:57.530
So it's actually random.

00:15:57.530 --> 00:16:00.370
There is no correlation between
when one particle leaves

00:16:00.370 --> 00:16:02.470
and the next particles
going to leave.

00:16:02.470 --> 00:16:04.840
And because it's a
truly random process,

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:08.290
these errors in the background
rate and the gross rate

00:16:08.290 --> 00:16:11.317
could add together or could
subtract from each other.

00:16:11.317 --> 00:16:13.150
In other words, one
might be a little higher

00:16:13.150 --> 00:16:15.692
than it should be, one might be
a little lower than it should

00:16:15.692 --> 00:16:16.300
be.

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:23.740
If you just add together
the two standard deviations,

00:16:23.740 --> 00:16:25.870
you actually always
get an overestimate

00:16:25.870 --> 00:16:30.180
of the true error,
because you're not

00:16:30.180 --> 00:16:32.820
accounting for the fact that
these two experiments may have

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:34.867
partially canceling errors.

00:16:34.867 --> 00:16:37.200
So in this case, that would
be your worst case scenario,

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:39.390
which is not your
most likely scenario.

00:16:39.390 --> 00:16:42.700
What you actually want is to
do what's called uncertainty

00:16:42.700 --> 00:16:45.960
in quadrature,
where you actually

00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:50.700
add up the sum of the square
roots of those errors.

00:16:50.700 --> 00:16:52.890
It kind of looks like the
magnitude of a vector,

00:16:52.890 --> 00:16:53.640
doesn't it?

00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:56.193
It kind of looks exactly like
the magnitude of a vector.

00:16:56.193 --> 00:16:58.110
So in this way, you're
accounting for the fact

00:16:58.110 --> 00:17:00.660
that more error
in each experiment

00:17:00.660 --> 00:17:03.930
does increase the error
on whatever net experiment

00:17:03.930 --> 00:17:06.390
you're doing, but not linearly.

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:09.390
Because sometimes you have
partially canceling errors.

00:17:09.390 --> 00:17:12.450
And with enough statistics,
if you count for long enough

00:17:12.450 --> 00:17:15.450
or you count enough counts, then
these things, on average, are

00:17:15.450 --> 00:17:20.025
going to add in quadrature,
which will come out to--

00:17:20.025 --> 00:17:24.160
and I want to make sure we don't
have any typos, so I'll just

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:26.020
keep the notes with me--

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:30.280
so you'd need the background
count over the background time

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:33.295
squared, plus those.

00:17:35.920 --> 00:17:37.613
There we go.

00:17:37.613 --> 00:17:39.280
And so, now, I'd like
to pose a question

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:44.860
to you, the same one that's
here in the problem set--

00:17:44.860 --> 00:17:47.020
how long do you have to
count in the smoke shop

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:49.200
to be 95% percent sure?

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:52.227
So let's say your count
rate's 5% uncertain.

00:17:52.227 --> 00:17:54.310
And we're going to spend
the rest of today's class

00:17:54.310 --> 00:17:58.340
taking apart that statement and
getting at what it should be.

00:17:58.340 --> 00:18:00.320
So again, what we
want to say is,

00:18:00.320 --> 00:18:07.440
how do you know that we're
95% confident of our count

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:12.540
rate plus or minus 5% error?

00:18:15.550 --> 00:18:17.637
That's the main
question for today.

00:18:17.637 --> 00:18:18.970
Does anyone know how we'd start?

00:18:23.237 --> 00:18:24.570
Anyone get to the reading today?

00:18:27.234 --> 00:18:28.650
I see some smiles.

00:18:28.650 --> 00:18:29.788
OK.

00:18:29.788 --> 00:18:31.080
We'll start from scratch, then.

00:18:34.475 --> 00:18:46.110
All right, So who here has
heard of a normal distribution

00:18:46.110 --> 00:18:47.160
before?

00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:48.210
A lot of you guys.

00:18:48.210 --> 00:18:49.080
Great.

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:53.490
The idea here is that with
enough counting statistics,

00:18:53.490 --> 00:18:57.270
this very rare event binomial
distribution approaches

00:18:57.270 --> 00:19:00.900
a normal distribution, where
you can say if you measure

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:03.540
a certain count rate-- let's say
this would be your mean count

00:19:03.540 --> 00:19:04.040
rate--

00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:14.450
to limits of plus
or minus 1 sigma

00:19:14.450 --> 00:19:22.680
or one standard deviation,
1 sigma gives you about 68%

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:30.160
confidence in your result.
Yeah, I spelled it right.

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:33.370
The reason for that is that if
you go plus or minus 1 sigma

00:19:33.370 --> 00:19:37.810
away from your true
average right here,

00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:42.880
you've filled in 68% of the area
under this normal distribution.

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:52.040
Similarly, if you go plus
2 sigma or minus 2 sigma,

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:57.400
it's around 95% confident.

00:19:57.400 --> 00:20:00.223
3 sigma is getting
towards 99 point--

00:20:00.223 --> 00:20:01.390
what was the number, again--

00:20:01.390 --> 00:20:03.840
I think it's 6.

00:20:03.840 --> 00:20:08.130
Maybe it's more like 98.5%.

00:20:08.130 --> 00:20:10.590
And then so on, and
so on, and so on.

00:20:10.590 --> 00:20:13.495
There's actually societies
called 6 sigma societies.

00:20:13.495 --> 00:20:15.120
And the way that they
get their name is

00:20:15.120 --> 00:20:17.220
we're so confident of
things we can predict them

00:20:17.220 --> 00:20:20.730
to 6 sigma, which is some
99 point a large number

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:24.970
of nines percentage of the area
under a normal distribution.

00:20:24.970 --> 00:20:27.750
So if I ask you,
how long do you have

00:20:27.750 --> 00:20:31.590
to count to be 95%
confident in your result,

00:20:31.590 --> 00:20:34.500
you have to give an answer
that will relate two

00:20:34.500 --> 00:20:36.890
times this standard deviation.

00:20:36.890 --> 00:20:39.650
And now we know the formula for
standard deviation of this net

00:20:39.650 --> 00:20:41.600
counting experiment.

00:20:41.600 --> 00:20:44.570
So we can formulate
our equation thusly--

00:20:44.570 --> 00:20:49.040
let's say in order to be 95%
confident, in other words, 2

00:20:49.040 --> 00:20:55.920
sigma, that our counting rate is
within 5% of the actual value,

00:20:55.920 --> 00:21:00.130
in other words, plus
or minus 5% error,

00:21:00.130 --> 00:21:02.710
we put our error
percentage here,

00:21:02.710 --> 00:21:04.930
and our true net
count rate there.

00:21:04.930 --> 00:21:10.210
So this part right here
tells us the 95% confidence.

00:21:10.210 --> 00:21:15.520
This part right here
is our 5% error.

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:18.190
And that part right
there is our count rate.

00:21:21.680 --> 00:21:25.370
So then we can substitute in
our expression for sigma--

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:27.950
our uncertainty in quadrature--
and find out things like,

00:21:27.950 --> 00:21:30.710
well, it depends on what the
information we're given is.

00:21:30.710 --> 00:21:32.870
Let's say before you
go to the smoke shop,

00:21:32.870 --> 00:21:36.590
you take your Geiger counter,
and for an extremely long time

00:21:36.590 --> 00:21:39.170
you count the background
counts somewhere.

00:21:39.170 --> 00:21:46.160
So let's say in this problem
the known quantities--

00:21:46.160 --> 00:21:48.500
we know our
background count rate,

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:51.480
because you can do that
at your leisure at home.

00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:56.550
And when I did this, it came out
to about 25 counts per minute.

00:21:56.550 --> 00:22:01.530
And known is the
background counting time.

00:22:01.530 --> 00:22:05.190
And when I did this, to
get within 95% confidence

00:22:05.190 --> 00:22:08.475
of 5% error, I had to
do this for 67 minutes.

00:22:12.440 --> 00:22:14.150
And now, all that's
left is we want

00:22:14.150 --> 00:22:22.740
to relate our net count rate
and our gross counting time,

00:22:22.740 --> 00:22:25.620
or our gross count rate and
our gross counting time,

00:22:25.620 --> 00:22:28.240
because it's the same thing.

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:29.860
So this is actually
how you decide

00:22:29.860 --> 00:22:32.320
how long you have to
sit in the smoke shop

00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:36.730
to count in order to
satisfy what we asked for--

00:22:36.730 --> 00:22:41.840
95% confidence that your
count rate is 5% error.

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:44.950
So let's start
substituting this out.

00:22:44.950 --> 00:22:46.960
That's not mine, so we
can get rid of that.

00:23:00.190 --> 00:23:02.880
So we'll take that expression
and substitute in everything

00:23:02.880 --> 00:23:04.050
we can.

00:23:04.050 --> 00:23:11.030
So 0.05 C n equals 2 sigma.

00:23:11.030 --> 00:23:14.760
And there's our
sigma expression,

00:23:14.760 --> 00:23:18.140
which I'll rewrite right here.

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:24.860
So we have see C b
over t b squared plus C

00:23:24.860 --> 00:23:28.790
g over t g squared.

00:23:31.870 --> 00:23:32.380
What's next?

00:23:34.980 --> 00:23:37.942
How do we relate t g and C g?

00:23:45.195 --> 00:23:47.070
Well, let's start with
the easy stuff, right?

00:23:47.070 --> 00:23:49.007
What can we cancel, or
square, or whatever?

00:23:49.007 --> 00:23:50.090
Just somebody yell it out.

00:23:53.938 --> 00:23:57.418
AUDIENCE: Do we have
numbers for these counts?

00:23:57.418 --> 00:23:58.210
MICHAEL SHORT: Yep.

00:23:58.210 --> 00:24:03.508
So we have numbers for C b
and t b, but not C g and t g.

00:24:03.508 --> 00:24:05.050
We have not yet
answered the question

00:24:05.050 --> 00:24:07.510
when you go into the smoke
shop and talk to the owner,

00:24:07.510 --> 00:24:08.770
and he says, fine,
you're going to sit here

00:24:08.770 --> 00:24:10.030
with the radiation detector.

00:24:10.030 --> 00:24:13.060
How long do you have to be
here, looking all weird?

00:24:13.060 --> 00:24:15.520
You want to have an answer.

00:24:15.520 --> 00:24:19.200
And so if you get some
initial estimate of C g,

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:22.170
you can tell him this is my
approximate t g, at which point

00:24:22.170 --> 00:24:24.212
he or she will say
yes or no, depending

00:24:24.212 --> 00:24:25.170
on how they're feeling.

00:24:27.800 --> 00:24:30.130
So why don't we just
start, divide by 2, right?

00:24:34.320 --> 00:24:36.084
Divide by 2.

00:24:36.084 --> 00:24:39.720
0.025.

00:24:39.720 --> 00:24:41.830
We can square both sides.

00:24:41.830 --> 00:24:43.860
And there's a C n there.

00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:51.556
Square both sides, and
we end up with 0.000625 C

00:24:51.556 --> 00:25:01.030
n squared equals C b
over t b squared plus C

00:25:01.030 --> 00:25:04.640
g over t g squared.

00:25:07.030 --> 00:25:08.530
There's lots of
ways to go about it.

00:25:08.530 --> 00:25:10.740
I want to make sure I
do the efficient one.

00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:14.980
Oh, I'm sorry those
aren't squared.

00:25:14.980 --> 00:25:22.100
Because our standard deviations
had the square root in them.

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:22.867
There we go.

00:25:22.867 --> 00:25:23.700
That's more like it.

00:25:26.370 --> 00:25:28.912
What's next?

00:25:28.912 --> 00:25:30.120
We've got too many variables.

00:25:30.120 --> 00:25:30.620
Yeah?

00:25:30.620 --> 00:25:34.233
AUDIENCE: I think there's still
a square value [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:34.233 --> 00:25:35.900
MICHAEL SHORT: Isn't
there still a what?

00:25:35.900 --> 00:25:37.400
AUDIENCE: Isn't
there a square value

00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:39.698
still under the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:25:39.698 --> 00:25:41.240
MICHAEL SHORT:
Because, in this case,

00:25:41.240 --> 00:25:44.680
the standard deviation is
the square root of the count

00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:46.900
rate over the time.

00:25:46.900 --> 00:25:48.310
So the standard
deviation squared

00:25:48.310 --> 00:25:51.860
is just count rate
overtime time.

00:25:51.860 --> 00:25:54.930
Was there an earlier
expression we have to correct?

00:25:54.930 --> 00:25:55.572
Yep.

00:25:55.572 --> 00:25:56.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:56.870 --> 00:25:59.790
That's where it came from.

00:25:59.790 --> 00:26:02.210
That's right.

00:26:02.210 --> 00:26:03.140
That's not.

00:26:03.140 --> 00:26:05.390
Because that's right.

00:26:05.390 --> 00:26:06.690
There we go.

00:26:06.690 --> 00:26:07.190
Good.

00:26:07.190 --> 00:26:08.820
Good, tracing out that.

00:26:08.820 --> 00:26:09.320
OK.

00:26:09.320 --> 00:26:15.032
Now that everything is
corrected here, what's next?

00:26:15.032 --> 00:26:16.240
We've got too many variables.

00:26:16.240 --> 00:26:17.770
Yeah?

00:26:17.770 --> 00:26:20.520
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
the standard deviation

00:26:20.520 --> 00:26:24.090
have units of [INAUDIBLE]?

00:26:24.090 --> 00:26:26.610
MICHAEL SHORT: Not
quite, because there's

00:26:26.610 --> 00:26:27.670
a count rate in here.

00:26:27.670 --> 00:26:29.250
So the units of
standard deviation,

00:26:29.250 --> 00:26:32.940
if this is square root
of count rate over time,

00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:37.110
which is the same as number of
counts times time over time,

00:26:37.110 --> 00:26:37.766
right?

00:26:37.766 --> 00:26:38.600
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:26:38.600 --> 00:26:39.790
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah.

00:26:39.790 --> 00:26:45.787
Because again, a count
rate is a number over--

00:26:45.787 --> 00:26:46.370
where'd it go.

00:26:46.370 --> 00:26:47.980
AUDIENCE: Number
over time squared.

00:26:47.980 --> 00:26:48.230
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah.

00:26:48.230 --> 00:26:49.610
Number over time squared.

00:26:49.610 --> 00:26:52.665
That doesn't sound right though.

00:26:52.665 --> 00:26:53.165
