01:04:15.310 --> 01:04:19.420
African children's toenails.

01:04:19.420 --> 01:04:20.350
That didn't happen.

01:04:20.350 --> 01:04:23.410
But I did analyze
my own toenails.

01:04:23.410 --> 01:04:25.340
Well, if you went
to somebody who

01:04:25.340 --> 01:04:28.960
was a little suspicious of
you, asking for toenails

01:04:28.960 --> 01:04:32.530
is a lot easier than
asking for a blood sample.

01:04:32.530 --> 01:04:37.510
Because people would give up
toenails-- it's not a big deal.

01:04:37.510 --> 01:04:39.700
Have you ever seen the
movie or read the book

01:04:39.700 --> 01:04:43.190
Civil Action, about the
superfund site in Woburn.

01:04:43.190 --> 01:04:46.540
It was a big old superfund
site, and Woburn had arsenic

01:04:46.540 --> 01:04:49.990
and chromium contamination.

01:04:49.990 --> 01:04:52.090
There used to be a lab--

01:04:52.090 --> 01:04:54.820
I forget which building it was
in-- that did a ton of research

01:04:54.820 --> 01:04:55.690
there.

01:04:55.690 --> 01:04:58.960
One of the things we
did in this lab was we

01:04:58.960 --> 01:05:05.020
collected baby hair samples
from people's scrapbooks.

01:05:05.020 --> 01:05:10.660
So we had baby hair
going back 50-60 years--

01:05:10.660 --> 01:05:14.340
dated, because everybody
knew how old their kid was--

01:05:14.340 --> 01:05:18.580
and we analyzed the hair samples
for arsenic and chromium,

01:05:18.580 --> 01:05:21.910
and then we plotted
out where they were,

01:05:21.910 --> 01:05:24.290
when the sample was taken,
and how close they were

01:05:24.290 --> 01:05:27.220
to some contaminated wells.

01:05:27.220 --> 01:05:30.370
And because we did a
fairly short of radiation,

01:05:30.370 --> 01:05:32.380
after a while the
activities died down

01:05:32.380 --> 01:05:34.910
and we gave the samples back.

01:05:34.910 --> 01:05:39.040
And we found that it didn't
correlate with the well

01:05:39.040 --> 01:05:42.010
water or the time when
the contamination was

01:05:42.010 --> 01:05:45.340
the worst, which made
people happy in retrospect,

01:05:45.340 --> 01:05:48.100
that the contamination
from that area

01:05:48.100 --> 01:05:50.830
didn't get into the well water.

01:05:50.830 --> 01:05:54.040
That was in the mid-90s or so.

01:05:54.040 --> 01:05:56.870
Anyway, that was
one of my samples.

01:05:56.870 --> 01:05:58.870
And the hair is a pain
in the neck to work with.

01:05:58.870 --> 01:06:01.510
So I hope none of you
give me hair samples.

01:06:01.510 --> 01:06:03.150
I won't run them.

01:06:03.150 --> 01:06:08.430
So let's go down
the hall, this way.

01:06:08.430 --> 01:06:10.246
You all got to follow.

01:06:10.246 --> 01:06:14.960
And so this is
just a fine powder.

01:06:14.960 --> 01:06:18.470
And it's fly ash from a
coal-fired power plant.

01:06:18.470 --> 01:06:23.210
Fly ash means the ash that goes
up the smokestack, as opposed

01:06:23.210 --> 01:06:25.820
to bottom ash which
is what falls down.

01:06:25.820 --> 01:06:31.730
And so, they collect a whole
hundreds of kilograms of fly

01:06:31.730 --> 01:06:35.990
ash, just homogenize it,
sieve it, send it out

01:06:35.990 --> 01:06:39.510
to a lot of labs to analyze--

01:06:39.510 --> 01:06:41.870
NIST is really good at this--

01:06:41.870 --> 01:06:42.920
take all the data.

01:06:42.920 --> 01:06:48.710
And so this ash is characterized
for about 20 elements or so.

01:06:48.710 --> 01:06:51.400
So when I run my
samples, if I were

01:06:51.400 --> 01:06:53.540
to run your samples
with standards,

01:06:53.540 --> 01:06:58.100
I'd run a little bit of
this, 5, 6, 7 milligrams.

01:06:58.100 --> 01:07:01.250
And I know what the
concentrations are in this.

01:07:01.250 --> 01:07:04.220
And so that's how I do
the comparative method.

01:07:04.220 --> 01:07:06.155
And so I got this.

01:07:06.155 --> 01:07:07.280
And they all look the same.

01:07:07.280 --> 01:07:11.540
And this is some soil from
Montana next to a mine,

01:07:11.540 --> 01:07:15.350
so it's nicely contaminated
with some metals.

01:07:15.350 --> 01:07:20.040
This is my IAEA mercury
and hair standard.

01:07:20.040 --> 01:07:21.650
But again, it's just
a little powder.

01:07:21.650 --> 01:07:24.440
And this is kind of what
everybody uses for standards.

01:07:24.440 --> 01:07:27.487
And you just kind of have
a whole collection of them.

01:07:27.487 --> 01:07:29.570
And depending on what
elements you're looking for,

01:07:29.570 --> 01:07:34.130
you try to mix and
match them so you

01:07:34.130 --> 01:07:35.600
cover what you
want without having

01:07:35.600 --> 01:07:37.652
to run five or six of them.

01:07:37.652 --> 01:07:42.400
This is my hot lab,
or one of my hot labs.

01:07:42.400 --> 01:07:44.600
You guys, last week,
or whatever it was,

01:07:44.600 --> 01:07:46.640
I came by-- so
this is the rabbit.

01:07:46.640 --> 01:07:48.080
Those you who
weren't there, these

01:07:48.080 --> 01:07:51.980
are called rabbits because
it's the little thing that runs

01:07:51.980 --> 01:07:53.870
through the pneumatic tube.

01:07:53.870 --> 01:07:56.220
You guys are doing
[INAUDIBLE] later today?

01:07:56.220 --> 01:07:56.720
Yeah.

01:07:56.720 --> 01:07:58.428
When you're sitting
at the control panel,

01:07:58.428 --> 01:08:00.350
there's a button, I
think it's to the left,

01:08:00.350 --> 01:08:02.450
and it says insert rabbit.

01:08:02.450 --> 01:08:05.780
And that's what this
is referring to.

01:08:05.780 --> 01:08:07.670
For longer radiations
there's a spot

01:08:07.670 --> 01:08:11.090
in the basement in the reactor
where they can get these,

01:08:11.090 --> 01:08:14.660
and they send them into
the irradiation location.

01:08:14.660 --> 01:08:16.399
For short
irradiations, like what

01:08:16.399 --> 01:08:18.149
you guys are going to
be doing in a month,

01:08:18.149 --> 01:08:20.810
I send them in from here.

01:08:20.810 --> 01:08:24.700
That's OK-- I just don't
want to bump into that thing.

01:08:24.700 --> 01:08:26.970
So this is one end of
the pneumatic system.

01:08:26.970 --> 01:08:30.670
And so I can put a couple
of samples in here.

01:08:30.670 --> 01:08:34.430
I stick it in that little tube
there, call the control room

01:08:34.430 --> 01:08:37.100
and say, OK, turn
a bunch of knobs,

01:08:37.100 --> 01:08:38.580
and switches, and whatnot.

01:08:38.580 --> 01:08:42.470
And it goes schwoonk,
and in about 15 seconds

01:08:42.470 --> 01:08:44.359
it's next to the
reactor to the core

01:08:44.359 --> 01:08:47.060
of the reactor in the graphite.

01:08:47.060 --> 01:08:48.410
I usually run shorts.

01:08:48.410 --> 01:08:51.800
I'll usually irradiate
for about 10 minutes.

01:08:51.800 --> 01:08:55.109
We usually let the sample sit in
the reactor for a little while.

01:08:55.109 --> 01:08:58.189
So the very short half-life
stuff decays away,

01:08:58.189 --> 01:09:00.050
and then it comes back out here.

01:09:00.050 --> 01:09:02.029
And the thing just kind
of shoots out there

01:09:02.029 --> 01:09:04.990
and bounces into here.

01:09:04.990 --> 01:09:08.569
And then pop open the
rabbit, and in that hood,

01:09:08.569 --> 01:09:10.220
pull the samples out.

01:09:10.220 --> 01:09:14.430
I usually try to
repackage the samples.

01:09:14.430 --> 01:09:16.399
So this is partly why I
asked for stuff that's

01:09:16.399 --> 01:09:19.939
one or two good solid pieces.

01:09:19.939 --> 01:09:23.450
Because then I can take it out
of whatever it was irradiated,

01:09:23.450 --> 01:09:27.170
put it in a clean bag
or vial, and that way we

01:09:27.170 --> 01:09:31.655
don't have to do a blank
subtraction for the sample.

01:09:31.655 --> 01:09:33.960
Does that make sense?

01:09:33.960 --> 01:09:36.620
Because, otherwise, if
I take a little vial,

01:09:36.620 --> 01:09:38.750
irradiate it, and
then count it, I'll

01:09:38.750 --> 01:09:43.279
also have whatever elements
are in the vial on the thing.

01:09:43.279 --> 01:09:47.270
For when I'm running standards--
and this is when if we're not

01:09:47.270 --> 01:09:49.540
running standards you don't
have to worry about this--

01:09:49.540 --> 01:09:53.420
that powdered standard stuff,
I never get that out of a bag.

01:09:53.420 --> 01:09:55.160
Because you'd never
get all of it out,

01:09:55.160 --> 01:09:58.880
and I'd have contamination
everywhere if I started cutting

01:09:58.880 --> 01:09:59.990
open those bags.

01:09:59.990 --> 01:10:03.350
So I do have to do a bag
correction for those.

01:10:03.350 --> 01:10:05.480
So when I do when
an irradiation,

01:10:05.480 --> 01:10:08.145
I always irradiate
a few empty bags,

01:10:08.145 --> 01:10:09.770
and then you do a
correction for those.

01:10:09.770 --> 01:10:13.040
Because the bags have got
aluminum, and antimony,

01:10:13.040 --> 01:10:15.650
and a bunch of things in them.

01:10:15.650 --> 01:10:17.510
And so then I take
a couple of samples,

01:10:17.510 --> 01:10:19.460
I throw them in a lead pig--

01:10:19.460 --> 01:10:21.770
so I've got a whole bunch
of these floating around--

01:10:21.770 --> 01:10:25.380
and I run it down the hall,
and throw it on a detector,

01:10:25.380 --> 01:10:26.210
and we count it.

01:10:26.210 --> 01:10:30.260
When we're doing shorts,
I'll irradiate two samples

01:10:30.260 --> 01:10:32.402
at a time, because I
have two detectors.

01:10:32.402 --> 01:10:33.860
When I used to have
four detectors,

01:10:33.860 --> 01:10:35.480
I ran for samples at a time.

01:10:35.480 --> 01:10:40.370
So you irradiate it,
repackage it, count it.

01:10:40.370 --> 01:10:43.880
While those pair of
samples are counting,

01:10:43.880 --> 01:10:46.730
you come down here, you
irradiate the next two,

01:10:46.730 --> 01:10:50.090
so that you're
just kind of always

01:10:50.090 --> 01:10:53.150
irradiating and counting.

01:10:53.150 --> 01:10:56.390
I usually do a 10-minute
irradiation for shorts.

01:10:56.390 --> 01:11:00.740
I'll do a fairly quick
count-- five minutes-- right

01:11:00.740 --> 01:11:02.690
after I get the
sample down there,

01:11:02.690 --> 01:11:06.050
and that's looking for
stuff with half-lifes

01:11:06.050 --> 01:11:07.640
under 10 minutes.

01:11:07.640 --> 01:11:10.370
The shortest half-life I
look for is for aluminum.

01:11:10.370 --> 01:11:12.317
It's 2 and 1/4 minutes.

01:11:12.317 --> 01:11:14.400
But things usually have a
lot of aluminum in them,

01:11:14.400 --> 01:11:18.410
so I see aluminum pretty well.

01:11:18.410 --> 01:11:20.030
For shorts, I'll
count all the way up

01:11:20.030 --> 01:11:25.340
to about sodium, which is
almost 15 hour half-life.

01:11:25.340 --> 01:11:28.040
Longer stuff, I'll do a
longer irradiation to count.

01:11:28.040 --> 01:11:30.200
There's a little overlap
on my shorts and longs.

01:11:30.200 --> 01:11:33.300
That helps me do QA on things.

01:11:33.300 --> 01:11:36.268
And if I run two standards,
I'll check the concentrations

01:11:36.268 --> 01:11:37.560
from one standard to the other.

01:11:37.560 --> 01:11:41.360
That's another little QA thing.

01:11:41.360 --> 01:11:42.902
What else we got?

01:11:42.902 --> 01:11:43.910
MICHAEL SHORT: What
question do you guys have?

01:11:43.910 --> 01:11:44.305
MICHAEL AMES: Questions.

01:11:44.305 --> 01:11:46.430
MICHAEL SHORT: Now that
you know how this done.

01:11:46.430 --> 01:11:47.660
MICHAEL AMES: It's
pretty straightforward.

01:11:47.660 --> 01:11:48.464
MICHAEL SHORT:
What sort of things

01:11:48.464 --> 01:11:49.797
are you going to be bringing in?

01:11:49.797 --> 01:11:51.357
MICHAEL AMES: Yeah,
what do we got?

01:11:51.357 --> 01:11:55.062
AUDIENCE: Probably middle
Bronze age pottery shirts.

01:11:55.062 --> 01:11:55.770
MICHAEL AMES: Oh.

01:11:55.770 --> 01:11:56.590
Yeah, yeah.

01:11:56.590 --> 01:11:57.380
OK.

01:11:57.380 --> 01:12:02.930
There is a lot of
archeology that NAA

01:12:02.930 --> 01:12:04.100
got used for that a lot.

01:12:04.100 --> 01:12:06.620
I don't think we
ever did it here.

01:12:06.620 --> 01:12:10.530
Fred Frey, who's a professor,
retired now, from EAPs--

01:12:10.530 --> 01:12:12.350
Earth, Atmospheric,
and Planetary--

01:12:12.350 --> 01:12:14.390
he did a lot of
geological samples.

01:12:14.390 --> 01:12:18.920
And I forget where it was that
they did all the archeology.

01:12:18.920 --> 01:12:20.540
One of the things
NAA is really good

01:12:20.540 --> 01:12:23.930
for is rare earth
elements, which

01:12:23.930 --> 01:12:27.350
are hard to measure
by other methods.

01:12:27.350 --> 01:12:29.480
I can get very low
limits on that.

01:12:29.480 --> 01:12:34.040
And by picking out various
rare earths and the ratios,

01:12:34.040 --> 01:12:36.821
it can help identify where
things are from in the world.

01:12:36.821 --> 01:12:37.654
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah.

01:12:37.654 --> 01:12:39.720
AUDIENCE: Can I use
a bird as a sample?

01:12:39.720 --> 01:12:42.200
MICHAEL AMES: If you give me
a little, tiny piece of it.

01:12:42.200 --> 01:12:42.742
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:12:42.742 --> 01:12:44.075
MICHAEL AMES: I mean, you know--

01:12:44.075 --> 01:12:44.960
I

01:12:44.960 --> 01:12:46.585
AUDIENCE: Like, how
small [INAUDIBLE]??

01:12:46.585 --> 01:12:48.377
MICHAEL AMES: Well,
see, that's the rabbit.

01:12:48.377 --> 01:12:50.038
So it's definitely
got to fit in there.

01:12:50.038 --> 01:12:50.580
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:12:50.580 --> 01:12:52.710
MICHAEL AMES: The
thing I really like--

01:12:52.710 --> 01:12:54.150
excuse me, where's my vials?

01:12:57.330 --> 01:12:59.760
I used to have some
smaller ones up here.

01:12:59.760 --> 01:13:04.350
But that should definitely
fit in one of those.

01:13:04.350 --> 01:13:05.437
Like, see that guy.

01:13:05.437 --> 01:13:06.473
AUDIENCE: OK

01:13:06.473 --> 01:13:07.890
MICHAEL AMES: My
usual description

01:13:07.890 --> 01:13:10.410
of what size sample
I like is if it's

01:13:10.410 --> 01:13:13.830
a piece that you would pick
up with a pair of tweezers.

01:13:13.830 --> 01:13:16.140
So not too small to pick up--

01:13:16.140 --> 01:13:17.340
to be able to find.

01:13:17.340 --> 01:13:19.875
So no powders.

01:13:19.875 --> 01:13:21.750
And you could maybe get
it with your fingers.

01:13:21.750 --> 01:13:26.130
But 20 milligrams, 50
milligrams, 100 milligrams

01:13:26.130 --> 01:13:28.520
is just in the right ballpark.

01:13:28.520 --> 01:13:30.020
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:13:30.020 --> 01:13:33.520
MICHAEL SHORT: What else are
you guys thinking of bringing?

01:13:33.520 --> 01:13:35.830
MICHAEL AMES: Doesn't matter.

01:13:35.830 --> 01:13:39.070
We'll look at what
comes in, and--

01:13:39.070 --> 01:13:40.930
yeah, I might veto
some things or not.

01:13:40.930 --> 01:13:42.460
But we'll see.

01:13:42.460 --> 01:13:43.442
We'll see what we got.

01:13:43.442 --> 01:13:44.858
MICHAEL SHORT: OK.

01:13:44.858 --> 01:13:47.155
AUDIENCE: What are
those little bricks for?

01:13:47.155 --> 01:13:49.030
MICHAEL AMES: Well, we
got bricks everywhere.

01:13:49.030 --> 01:13:52.660
So when I get the
sample out of there,

01:13:52.660 --> 01:13:54.640
I do the repackaging in here.

01:13:54.640 --> 01:13:57.700
And so this is just
shielding between the samples

01:13:57.700 --> 01:14:00.400
I'm working on and myself.

01:14:00.400 --> 01:14:01.960
I don't have my
dosimeter on now,

01:14:01.960 --> 01:14:05.350
but I usually have got the
symmetry and a ring badge.

01:14:05.350 --> 01:14:07.120
And then it kind
of comes over here,

01:14:07.120 --> 01:14:09.610
and this is where
the heat sealer is.

01:14:09.610 --> 01:14:12.950
So I can heat seal it here, and
then I'll have a pig over here.

01:14:12.950 --> 01:14:14.950
MICHAEL SHORT: They're
just painted lead bricks?

01:14:14.950 --> 01:14:16.390
MICHAEL AMES: Yeah, these
are just painted lead bricks.

01:14:16.390 --> 01:14:19.130
And you know, these have
been here longer than I have.

01:14:19.130 --> 01:14:22.210
And sometimes things
just are somewhere,

01:14:22.210 --> 01:14:23.350
and you never move them.

01:14:23.350 --> 01:14:26.140
These, I think, are
older than me too.

01:14:26.140 --> 01:14:30.580
This lab has been doing NAA
since the '70s, I think.

01:14:33.744 --> 01:14:34.715
Anybody else?

01:14:34.715 --> 01:14:36.090
AUDIENCE: Is there
a single brick

01:14:36.090 --> 01:14:38.940
that I could just hold
to see how heavy it is?

01:14:38.940 --> 01:14:40.560
MICHAEL AMES: The
full size bricks--

01:14:40.560 --> 01:14:43.770
like, that size, 2 inches,
by 4 inches, by 8 inches,

01:14:43.770 --> 01:14:46.380
weighs about 25 pounds.

01:14:46.380 --> 01:14:49.230
There's usually a bunch
of them floating around.

01:14:49.230 --> 01:14:52.530
Here, you want this game?

01:14:52.530 --> 01:14:55.627
That one's not quite full size.

01:14:55.627 --> 01:14:56.210
AUDIENCE: Wow.

01:14:56.210 --> 01:14:57.390
That's pretty heavy.

01:14:57.390 --> 01:14:58.030
MICHAEL AMES: They're heavy.

01:14:58.030 --> 01:14:58.712
They're lead.

01:14:58.712 --> 01:14:59.920
Anybody else want to toss it?

01:14:59.920 --> 01:15:00.855
No, OK.

01:15:00.855 --> 01:15:04.740
[LAUGHTER]

01:15:04.740 --> 01:15:06.840
When people ask me--

01:15:06.840 --> 01:15:09.220
because I work in the
reactor, as well-- they say,

01:15:09.220 --> 01:15:11.012
is there anything
dangerous in the reactor?

01:15:11.012 --> 01:15:14.900
The dangerous thing is dropping
lead bricks on your feet.

01:15:14.900 --> 01:15:16.770
So I've got steel toast.

01:15:16.770 --> 01:15:19.855
If I miss the toe, I'd
probably break my--

01:15:19.855 --> 01:15:21.620
I don't want to think about it.

01:15:21.620 --> 01:15:24.150
And they move much bigger
things in the reactor.

01:15:24.150 --> 01:15:25.740
Have you toured the reactor yet?

01:15:25.740 --> 01:15:27.000
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:29.000
MICHAEL AMES: So there's
that giant crane there,

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:31.713
and they move five-ton
pieces a shielding.

01:15:31.713 --> 01:15:33.630
And that's the other
dangerous thing in there,

01:15:33.630 --> 01:15:35.400
dropping really big things.

01:15:35.400 --> 01:15:37.140
We've never dropped
anything that big.

01:15:39.663 --> 01:15:42.080
I think somebody dropped a
steel plate on their foot once.

01:15:42.080 --> 01:15:43.626
That was about the worst of it.

01:15:43.626 --> 01:15:45.530
[LAUGHTER]

01:15:45.530 --> 01:15:48.292
You know, like, four-foot,
half-inch steel-- boom.

01:15:48.292 --> 01:15:50.250
MICHAEL SHORT: That's
what happened to my foot.

01:15:50.250 --> 01:15:51.042
MICHAEL AMES: Yeah.

01:15:51.042 --> 01:15:51.990
OK, good.

01:15:51.990 --> 01:15:53.790
And people trip and
fall off ladders.

01:15:53.790 --> 01:15:55.800
And it's the usual
industrial accidents.

01:15:55.800 --> 01:15:59.347
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
cut off your toe.

01:15:59.347 --> 01:16:00.180
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:16:00.180 --> 01:16:01.310
AUDIENCE: Well, my
toes are still here.

01:16:01.310 --> 01:16:01.540
MICHAEL AMES: Good.

01:16:01.540 --> 01:16:02.060
Yeah.

01:16:02.060 --> 01:16:04.850
I mean, I've broken
a few, but not here.

01:16:04.850 --> 01:16:05.850
MICHAEL SHORT: So, cool.

01:16:05.850 --> 01:16:06.680
Thanks a ton, Mike.

01:16:06.680 --> 01:16:07.490
MICHAEL AMES: Sure.

01:16:07.490 --> 01:16:09.500
And I'll see you guys
in a month or something

01:16:09.500 --> 01:16:12.860
and have fun
running the reactor.

01:16:12.860 --> 01:16:15.230
FRANK WARMSLEY: Well,
good day, folks.

01:16:15.230 --> 01:16:18.830
You guys are here to do an
experiment on the reactor.

01:16:18.830 --> 01:16:20.220
It's in two parts.

01:16:20.220 --> 01:16:22.305
The first part is
raising reactor power.

01:16:25.630 --> 01:16:28.620
The first is raising
reactor power

01:16:28.620 --> 01:16:32.950
using a low worth absorber
called a regulating rod.

01:16:32.950 --> 01:16:35.490
And then the second part will
be lowering reactor power

01:16:35.490 --> 01:16:37.410
using a high worth absorber.

01:16:37.410 --> 01:16:40.620
And the high worth absorber,
things will moved much faster.

01:16:40.620 --> 01:16:43.680
And we don't want
to run into a chance

01:16:43.680 --> 01:16:45.760
if you accidentally
going too high,

01:16:45.760 --> 01:16:49.050
so that's why we use a low
worth absorber on the way up

01:16:49.050 --> 01:16:51.900
and a high worth
absorber on the way down.

01:16:51.900 --> 01:16:53.970
And I just want to
show you the controls.

01:16:53.970 --> 01:16:56.160
With me today is Tim.

01:16:56.160 --> 01:16:58.260
To actually do
this experiment, we

01:16:58.260 --> 01:17:00.900
need two licensed
people in here,

01:17:00.900 --> 01:17:03.510
one at least has a
senior reactor operator.

01:17:03.510 --> 01:17:05.370
Both Tim and I are
both senior licenses,

01:17:05.370 --> 01:17:07.050
so we have that covered.

01:17:07.050 --> 01:17:09.240
The only way you can actually
do these manipulations

01:17:09.240 --> 01:17:11.870
are if you're in my
training program--

01:17:11.870 --> 01:17:14.340
I'm the training supervisor
for the facility--

01:17:14.340 --> 01:17:18.360
or you're in a program that
needs you to actually operate

01:17:18.360 --> 01:17:19.770
the reactor.

01:17:19.770 --> 01:17:24.540
And the program you guys
are in fits that definition.

01:17:24.540 --> 01:17:27.840
So I just want to show you some
of the controls of the reactor.

01:17:27.840 --> 01:17:30.630
First, we have our
shim blade controller.

01:17:30.630 --> 01:17:36.600
This basically moves one of
six shim blades at a time.

01:17:36.600 --> 01:17:38.790
The one that's selected
has a slide on it.

01:17:38.790 --> 01:17:41.940
And we can change which one's
selected with the shim blade

01:17:41.940 --> 01:17:44.730
selector switch.

01:17:44.730 --> 01:17:46.710
This switch here is
a regulating rod.

01:17:46.710 --> 01:17:50.750
This one will allow you to move
the regulating rod up and down.

01:17:50.750 --> 01:17:52.440
Our blades our fixed
speed, meaning they

01:17:52.440 --> 01:17:58.800
can only move at the exact
same rate at all times.

01:17:58.800 --> 01:18:01.890
Moving the shim blade
in an upward direction

01:18:01.890 --> 01:18:04.920
or the regulating rod
in upwards direction,

01:18:04.920 --> 01:18:07.680
take an underhand
grip and pull up

01:18:07.680 --> 01:18:11.100
or twist upwards until it stops.

01:18:11.100 --> 01:18:13.890
Moving it just a little
bit doesn't move anything.

01:18:13.890 --> 01:18:16.440
You have to move all
the way until it stops,

01:18:16.440 --> 01:18:20.310
and then the absorber will
move in the outward direction.

01:18:20.310 --> 01:18:23.220
If you want the blade
to stop just release it.

01:18:23.220 --> 01:18:25.950
It's spring-loaded and will go
back to the neutral position

01:18:25.950 --> 01:18:27.360
and stop moving.

01:18:27.360 --> 01:18:30.030
If you want to drive something
in the inward position,

01:18:30.030 --> 01:18:33.480
take an overhand grip
and twist downwards,

01:18:33.480 --> 01:18:35.220
and that will drive
the absorber in.

01:18:35.220 --> 01:18:36.990
Once again, let go.

01:18:36.990 --> 01:18:40.800
It'll snap back up and stop
the motion of the blade

01:18:40.800 --> 01:18:43.890
or the regulating rod.

01:18:43.890 --> 01:18:46.770
The experiment we're doing is
basically change reactor power

01:18:46.770 --> 01:18:48.810
by half a megawatt.

01:18:48.810 --> 01:18:51.930
And we're currently
at 500 kilowatts

01:18:51.930 --> 01:18:55.530
we're going bring the
reactor up to 1 megawatt

01:18:55.530 --> 01:18:59.770
and then bring it back
down to 500 kilowatts.

01:18:59.770 --> 01:19:03.030
So before we can do this, you
have to log into our log book

01:19:03.030 --> 01:19:05.790
as a trainee on console.

01:19:05.790 --> 01:19:08.310
We'll show you the proper
way to make the entries.

01:19:08.310 --> 01:19:12.180
As you make those entries,
you'll go ahead and then

01:19:12.180 --> 01:19:15.840
do the actual movement itself.

01:19:15.840 --> 01:19:20.040
Sp the first one is going to
be using a regular rod to move

01:19:20.040 --> 01:19:21.870
the reactor power up.

01:19:21.870 --> 01:19:23.520
What's the reactor power?

01:19:23.520 --> 01:19:25.860
We have about nine
different instruments

01:19:25.860 --> 01:19:28.410
that tell us what the reactor
power is at all times.

01:19:28.410 --> 01:19:30.660
But the ones we're going to
be paying attention to are

01:19:30.660 --> 01:19:32.730
channel seven 7 and channel 9.

01:19:32.730 --> 01:19:35.490
These two channels are what
we used to basically tell us

01:19:35.490 --> 01:19:36.960
what the wrecked power is.

01:19:36.960 --> 01:19:41.580
Channel 7 is what we control
our automatic control at.

01:19:41.580 --> 01:19:43.620
If you watch the
regulating rod, you'll

01:19:43.620 --> 01:19:46.890
see it move up and
down on its own.

01:19:46.890 --> 01:19:49.710
That's because
it's changing power

01:19:49.710 --> 01:19:52.540
based on what it sees
channel 7 is doing.

01:19:52.540 --> 01:19:55.650
So if channel 7 sees that the
power level's going too low,

01:19:55.650 --> 01:19:58.290
it'll cause the regulating
rod to drive outwards

01:19:58.290 --> 01:20:00.000
to increase the
amount of neutrons

01:20:00.000 --> 01:20:02.760
making the reactor power go up.

01:20:02.760 --> 01:20:05.760
Channel 9 is a
linear power channel,

01:20:05.760 --> 01:20:09.240
and it basically tells us
what the power level is based

01:20:09.240 --> 01:20:11.640
on a chart that we create.

01:20:11.640 --> 01:20:14.760
So it's not showing you
megawatts, or kilowatts,

01:20:14.760 --> 01:20:17.670
or anything like that, it's
showing you a current coming

01:20:17.670 --> 01:20:18.390
from a chamber.

01:20:18.390 --> 01:20:20.220
And that current
is then converted

01:20:20.220 --> 01:20:23.350
into megawatts and so forth.

01:20:23.350 --> 01:20:28.620
So right now, we're at 500
kilowatts, 8.5 microamps,

01:20:28.620 --> 01:20:30.190
on this channel.

01:20:30.190 --> 01:20:33.945
And that's 8.5 microamps
equals 550 kilowatts.

01:20:33.945 --> 01:20:35.820
You're going to be
bringing a record up to 1.

01:20:35.820 --> 01:20:42.030
Megawatt and since it's linear,
it'll be double that-- so 17.1.

01:20:42.030 --> 01:20:44.700
Now, you want to be careful
when you raise reactor power.

01:20:44.700 --> 01:20:46.740
So when you start to
add power to the reactor

01:20:46.740 --> 01:20:51.300
by raising a regulating rod, you
don't want to keep raising it

01:20:51.300 --> 01:20:53.700
until you reach your
value, because you

01:20:53.700 --> 01:20:56.410
have to actually stop the
power increase as well.

01:20:56.410 --> 01:20:59.010
So we have two rules
that we have to follow--

01:20:59.010 --> 01:21:03.210
one, at the power level
we're at, we have period--

01:21:03.210 --> 01:21:04.710
the reactor period.

01:21:04.710 --> 01:21:06.210
The reactor period
is amount of time

01:21:06.210 --> 01:21:08.010
it takes reactor
power to increase.

01:21:08.010 --> 01:21:09.600
At the power level
we're at, we're

01:21:09.600 --> 01:21:13.500
not allowed to go shorter
than a 100-second period.

01:21:13.500 --> 01:21:16.770
So here is one of
three periods meters--

01:21:16.770 --> 01:21:21.000
one here, one here, which
is selectable between two

01:21:21.000 --> 01:21:23.078
different meters.

01:21:23.078 --> 01:21:24.870
So as you're pulling
up the regulating rod,

01:21:24.870 --> 01:21:26.400
one of the things
you have to watch

01:21:26.400 --> 01:21:29.520
is to make sure that the reactor
period doesn't go shorter

01:21:29.520 --> 01:21:31.080
than a 100-second period.

01:21:31.080 --> 01:21:33.390
If it does, you have
to stop pulling blades.

01:21:33.390 --> 01:21:35.220
The other thing we
have to watch for

01:21:35.220 --> 01:21:38.970
is to make sure that the
power level, channel 9,

01:21:38.970 --> 01:21:41.070
doesn't exceed where
you're going to.

01:21:41.070 --> 01:21:43.110
Not only not exceed,
but we also want

01:21:43.110 --> 01:21:46.740
to make sure that you can
actually control the reactor.

01:21:46.740 --> 01:21:48.870
It's called
feasibility of control.

01:21:48.870 --> 01:21:51.420
And what that means is
when you get to about 80%

01:21:51.420 --> 01:21:52.962
of the power level
you're going to--

01:21:52.962 --> 01:21:54.420
since we're going
up to 1 megawatt,

01:21:54.420 --> 01:21:56.340
that's about 800 kilowatts--

01:21:56.340 --> 01:22:00.000
you want to be able to drive
the absorber in and hold

01:22:00.000 --> 01:22:01.050
the absorber in.

01:22:01.050 --> 01:22:03.600
You'll drive the
regulating rod inwards.

01:22:03.600 --> 01:22:05.430
And watch that
channel nine value.

01:22:05.430 --> 01:22:09.480
It'll slow until it actually
starts to go down again.

01:22:09.480 --> 01:22:12.592
Once it reaches that value
and you see it going down,

01:22:12.592 --> 01:22:14.550
you now know that you
could control the reactor

01:22:14.550 --> 01:22:16.750
and keep it from going away--

01:22:16.750 --> 01:22:19.080
rack power increasing
continuously.

01:22:19.080 --> 01:22:21.120
So what we're going
to do is have you

01:22:21.120 --> 01:22:24.240
when you reach 80% of the
power level you're going to,

01:22:24.240 --> 01:22:27.570
which happens to
be 800 kilowatts,

01:22:27.570 --> 01:22:30.540
you're going to start increasing
or lengthening the period

01:22:30.540 --> 01:22:34.500
by driving the absorber
back in the regulating rod.

01:22:34.500 --> 01:22:36.900
And you'll keep holding it
in until you see the number

01:22:36.900 --> 01:22:40.275
not only stop increasing, but
actually go down a little bit.

01:22:40.275 --> 01:22:42.150
As soon as you see it
going down a little bit

01:22:42.150 --> 01:22:44.315
and go of the
regulating rod, You

01:22:44.315 --> 01:22:45.940
haven't stopped the
power at this time,

01:22:45.940 --> 01:22:50.390
you've just decreased
how fast it's going up.

01:22:50.390 --> 01:22:52.160
And then the power
level will sill go up,

01:22:52.160 --> 01:22:55.410
but a much slower rate
than it was before.

01:22:55.410 --> 01:22:58.740
And once it reaches the power
level you want to stop at,

01:22:58.740 --> 01:23:01.700
the 1 megawatt, keep driving
the regulating rod in

01:23:01.700 --> 01:23:04.160
to hold it at that power level.

01:23:04.160 --> 01:23:06.080
Once you're at that
power level, you're

01:23:06.080 --> 01:23:08.900
going to make an entry
in a log book that

01:23:08.900 --> 01:23:10.580
basically says you
made it to the power

01:23:10.580 --> 01:23:12.680
level you're going to.

01:23:12.680 --> 01:23:15.560
And then we'll go down in power.

01:23:15.560 --> 01:23:17.660
So once again, you make
an entry in a log book

01:23:17.660 --> 01:23:21.140
that says I'm going to lower
ranked power to 500 kilowatts,

01:23:21.140 --> 01:23:23.350
and then this time
we'll use a shim blade.

01:23:23.350 --> 01:23:26.030
The shim blade is worth a lot
more than a regulating rod--

01:23:26.030 --> 01:23:30.470
about 10 times the
regulating rod, so things

01:23:30.470 --> 01:23:32.053
will happen much faster.

01:23:32.053 --> 01:23:33.470
So you'll be able
to drive this in

01:23:33.470 --> 01:23:36.920
and reactor power will change
much faster than before.

01:23:36.920 --> 01:23:39.410
Same thing-- as you get closer
to the power level you start

01:23:39.410 --> 01:23:41.930
at, the 500 kilowatts,
you don't want

01:23:41.930 --> 01:23:43.670
to undershoot and go too low.

01:23:43.670 --> 01:23:48.500
So right around 600 kilowatts
or so, start driving or shim

01:23:48.500 --> 01:23:50.847
blade out to slow down
how quickly the power

01:23:50.847 --> 01:23:51.680
level is going down.

01:23:54.240 --> 01:23:57.710
And once you get back to the
place where you started it,

01:23:57.710 --> 01:24:00.650
we'll use a regulating
rod to fine tune it

01:24:00.650 --> 01:24:03.210
to keep the reactor power
where would want it to be.

01:24:03.210 --> 01:24:05.370
There'll be another
logbook entry,

01:24:05.370 --> 01:24:07.627
and your time on the
console will be completed.

01:24:10.830 --> 01:24:14.383
So with us today we actually
have two MIT students

01:24:14.383 --> 01:24:16.050
who are actually in
my training program,

01:24:16.050 --> 01:24:22.112
and they've actually done a lot
of these manipulations already.

01:24:22.112 --> 01:24:23.070
AUDIENCE: Ladies first.

01:24:23.070 --> 01:24:23.520
FRANK WARMSLEY: Sarah.

01:24:23.520 --> 01:24:24.030
Let's go.

01:24:24.030 --> 01:24:24.947
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:24:24.947 --> 01:24:29.030
It's been so long
since I've done one.

01:24:29.030 --> 01:24:31.450
FRANK WARMSLEY: I'll take that.

01:24:31.450 --> 01:24:35.020
So, normally, we sit and watch.

01:24:35.020 --> 01:24:38.840
If, at any time, you don't feel
comfortable doing something,

01:24:38.840 --> 01:24:39.940
let us know.

01:24:39.940 --> 01:24:42.778
We'll ask you just to take
your hands off the console,

01:24:42.778 --> 01:24:44.320
and we'll take care
of doing whatever

01:24:44.320 --> 01:24:47.110
is necessary to keep
the reactor safe.

01:24:47.110 --> 01:24:51.970
But be aware, we're
a factor of 10

01:24:51.970 --> 01:24:55.078
lower than where we would
automatically scram at so.

01:24:55.078 --> 01:24:56.620
So it would be very
difficult for you

01:24:56.620 --> 01:24:58.037
to get to someplace
where it would

01:24:58.037 --> 01:25:00.595
cause a problem without
us being able to stop it.

01:25:06.750 --> 01:25:08.920
I don't know if you want
to move or anything,

01:25:08.920 --> 01:25:16.060
but the supervisor normally
sits kind of right in your way

01:25:16.060 --> 01:25:20.756
so that they can keep
eye on what's happening.

01:25:20.756 --> 01:25:23.182
AUDIENCE: Are we doing doing
any announcing for these?

01:25:25.900 --> 01:25:29.130
FRANK WARMSLEY: You can go
ahead and make the announcement

01:25:29.130 --> 01:25:32.138
that we're starting
power manipulations,

01:25:32.138 --> 01:25:34.680
and then the last person will
make an announcement that we're

01:25:34.680 --> 01:25:36.898
done with power manipulations.

01:25:44.157 --> 01:25:45.865
AUDIENCE: Commencing
power manipulations.

01:25:45.865 --> 01:25:47.842
Commencing power manipulations.

01:25:54.770 --> 01:25:57.350
FRANK WARMSLEY: Right now,
the reactor is on autocontrol.

01:25:57.350 --> 01:25:58.820
And when we do
these manipulations,

01:25:58.820 --> 01:26:02.290
the reactor operator is
going to take manual control.

01:26:02.290 --> 01:26:04.400
That'll cause an
alarm to come in.

01:26:04.400 --> 01:26:07.050
And this will only happen
for the first time.

01:26:07.050 --> 01:26:09.590
So one of the things she's
going to do after she

01:26:09.590 --> 01:26:10.833
makes her logbook entry--

01:26:10.833 --> 01:26:12.250
AUDIENCE: Are we
filling this out?

01:26:12.250 --> 01:26:14.167
FRANK WARMSLEY: No, we'll
do that at the end--

01:26:14.167 --> 01:26:16.760
is she'll take manual
control of the reactor,

01:26:16.760 --> 01:26:19.490
an alarm will come in on
console, and she'll answer it.

01:26:19.490 --> 01:26:21.698
And that should be the only
time you hear this alarm,

01:26:21.698 --> 01:26:23.780
because we'll leave
it on manual control

01:26:23.780 --> 01:26:28.332
until the final participant
has done their manipulations.

01:26:30.936 --> 01:26:31.769
AUDIENCE: All right.

01:26:31.769 --> 01:26:34.905
I hope to get to 1 megawatt
at 17.11 [INAUDIBLE]..

01:26:34.905 --> 01:26:35.697
FRANK WARMSLEY: OK.

01:26:40.116 --> 01:26:43.553
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:26:46.499 --> 01:26:51.876
[ELECTRONIC SOUND]

01:26:51.876 --> 01:26:53.459
FRANK WARMSLEY: Now,
she's pulling out

01:26:53.459 --> 01:26:57.530
the red rod all the way.

01:26:57.530 --> 01:27:00.270
You see the red rod
number going up.

01:27:00.270 --> 01:27:02.910
The period is getting shorter.

01:27:02.910 --> 01:27:04.560
It's no longer at infinity.

01:27:04.560 --> 01:27:06.780
It's getting closer
to 100 second.

01:27:06.780 --> 01:27:10.314
And channel 7 and channel
9 are increasing in value.

01:27:20.160 --> 01:27:23.120
Another way you can see
it is we have a display

01:27:23.120 --> 01:27:25.260
on the front the operator.

01:27:25.260 --> 01:27:28.140
Those three
displays, two of them

01:27:28.140 --> 01:27:31.530
are just for evaluation only.

01:27:31.530 --> 01:27:34.950
We don't actually use those
to control the reactor.

01:27:34.950 --> 01:27:37.650
They're based on a system
that hasn't been approved yet.

01:27:37.650 --> 01:27:40.570
But we're testing them to
see how well they work.

01:27:40.570 --> 01:27:43.890
So you can see that the
power level on the far left

01:27:43.890 --> 01:27:45.498
is going up.

01:27:45.498 --> 01:27:47.790
The middle one is showing
what the actual power level--

01:27:47.790 --> 01:27:49.340
we started at 500 kilowatts.

01:27:49.340 --> 01:27:52.320
It's already up to 630
kilowatts and increasing.

01:27:52.320 --> 01:27:54.300
And the period that
was at infinity

01:27:54.300 --> 01:27:55.916
is now around 160 seconds.

01:28:11.852 --> 01:28:16.620
So she's watching, and she sees
the 800 kilowatt value here

01:28:16.620 --> 01:28:20.350
on channel 7 or channel
9, and she's started

01:28:20.350 --> 01:28:22.320
to driving the regulating ride.

01:28:22.320 --> 01:28:27.990
So she's slowing down how quick
the power increases going.

01:28:27.990 --> 01:28:31.170
And you see the
period lengthening.

01:28:31.170 --> 01:28:34.530
It's no longer at
150-160 seconds.

01:28:34.530 --> 01:28:37.440
It's going closer
to infinity again.

01:28:37.440 --> 01:28:39.450
So she's proving that she
could stop the reactor

01:28:39.450 --> 01:28:42.860
power if she continued driving
in this regulating rod.

01:28:55.235 --> 01:28:56.918
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
back on auto?

01:28:56.918 --> 01:28:57.710
FRANK WARMSLEY: No.

01:29:06.867 --> 01:29:09.095
She's closing in
on the 1 megawatt.

01:29:21.030 --> 01:29:24.370
One of the things the note
is that when she started,

01:29:24.370 --> 01:29:27.610
the [INAUDIBLE] was
around 0300, 0310,

01:29:27.610 --> 01:29:29.710
and she's almost
right back to there.

01:29:29.710 --> 01:29:33.430
When you raise reactor power,
you basically open up a valve

01:29:33.430 --> 01:29:34.472
and let more neutrons in.

01:29:34.472 --> 01:29:36.597
And when you get to the
place where you want to be,

01:29:36.597 --> 01:29:38.350
you basically close
that valve again.

01:29:38.350 --> 01:29:43.100
So you basically add reactivity
and then stop that reactivity

01:29:43.100 --> 01:29:46.330
addition by bringing the
absorbers back to about

01:29:46.330 --> 01:29:48.860
where they started from.

01:29:48.860 --> 01:29:52.270
AUDIENCE: We're at 17.1

01:29:52.270 --> 01:29:53.770
